Anonymous Tue 28 Jun 2022 21:06:52 No.48903040 Report
Quoted By: >>48903128 >>48903180 >>48903204 >>48903475
>>48902814
As another write anon.

If you have trouble establishing the habit, make it as distinct as possible. A lot of people struggle because they try to write on the same computer they browse, watch youtube, or listen to music on. It's hard to get out of the headspace of a well worn groove like that.

Take a laptop somewhere else, even just another room in your house, maybe listen to a specific type of music you enjoy but don't listen to regularly to promote a different experience for as many senses as possible. Light a candle or incense to anchor a smell to what you are doing. Once you have the habit established you'll find you can skip most of these steps, but anchoring as many senses as you can early on really helps.

I know of one successful writer who writes his (nonfiction) books by picking a movie and putting it on in the background until the book is done. Which resulted in him watching Babe something like 600 times on his largest book, but it had gentle background music and no distracting action sequences so it worked for what he was using it for. The point was that so long as the movie was playing he was working, and it helped to control his ability to distract himself.
